   718	
   719	I. Introduction
   720	
   721	Table of Contents
   722	1. Introduction
   723	
   724	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   725	
   726	Chapter 1. Introduction
   727	
   728	Introduction
   729	
   730	This is the Linux Standard Base Work In Progress 20030708 . An implementation
   731	of anything in this document may not claim to be an implementation of the Linux
   732	Standard Base until such time as the feature moves into the Linux Standards
   733	Base Specification.
   734	
   735	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   736	
   737	Purpose
   738	
   739	The Linux Standard Base (LSB) defines a system interface for compiled
   740	applications and a minimal environment for support of installation scripts. Its
   741	purpose is to enable a uniform industry standard environment for high-volume
   742	applications conforming to the LSB.
   743	
   744	The LSB defines a binary interface for application programs that are compiled
   745	and packaged for LSB-conforming implementations on many different hardware
   746	architectures. Since a binary specification must include information specific
   747	to the computer processor architecture for which it is intended, it is not
   748	possible for a single document to specify the interface for all possible
   749	LSB-conforming implementations. Therefore, the LSB is a family of
   750	specifications, rather than a single one.
   751	
   752	The LSB is composed of two basic parts: A common specification ("generic LSB"
   753	or "gLSB") describing those parts of the interface that remain constant across
   754	all implementations of the LSB, and an architecture-specific specification
   755	("archLSB") describing the parts of the interface that vary by processor
   756	architecture. Together, the generic LSB and the architecture-specific
   757	supplement for a single hardware architecture provide a complete interface
   758	specification for compiled application programs on systems that share a common
   759	hardware architecture.
   760	
   761	This document is the generic LSB. It must be used in conjunction with an
   762	architecture-specific supplement. Whenever a section of this specification must
   763	be supplemented by architecture-specific information, this document includes a
   764	reference to the architecture supplement. Architecture supplements may also
   765	contain additional information that is not referenced here.
   766	
   767	This document should be used in conjunction with the documents it references.
   768	This document enumerates the system components it includes, but descriptions of
   769	those components may be included entirely or partly in this document, partly in
   770	other documents, or entirely in other reference documents. For example, the
   771	section that describes system service routines includes a list of the system
   772	routines supported in this interface, formal declarations of the data
   773	structures they use that are visible to applications, and a pointer to the
   774	underlying referenced specification for information about the syntax and
   775	semantics of each call. Only those routines not described in standards
   776	referenced by this document, or extensions to those standards, are described in
   777	the detail. Information referenced in this way is as much a part of this
   778	document as is the information explicitly included here.
   779	
   780	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   781	
   782	Related Standards
   783	
   784	The specifications listed below are referenced in whole or in part by the Linux
   785	Standard Base. When a specification is referenced in a way that imposes a
   786	requirement (for example, "foo must behave as specified in the XyzzySpec"),
   787	then the relevant requirements of that specification apply as if they were part
   788	of the LSB itself. However, if the LSB refers to a specification without
   789	imposing a requirement, then it is merely a reference and does not add
   790	additional requirements. The LSB may refer to a portion of a specification (for
   791	example, to define a specific function or group of functions); in such cases,
   792	only the explicitly referenced portion of the specification applies.
   793	
   794	Table 1-1. Related Standards
   795

   911	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   912	
   913	Relevant Libraries
   914	
   915	The libraries listed here shall be available on a Linux Standard Base system.
   916	This list may be supplemented or amended by the architecture-specific
   917	specifications.
   918	
   919	Table 1-2. Standard Libraries Names

   956	Supplement
   957	
   958	+------------------------+
   959	|Library   |Runtime Name |
   960	|----------+-------------|
   961	|libm      |See archLSB  |
   962	|----------+-------------|

   966	+------------------------+
   967	
   968	These libraries will be in an implementation-dependent directory which the
   969	dynamic linker will search by default.
   970	
   971	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   972	
   973	How to Use this Standard
   974	
   975	The complete LSB specification is composed of this generic LSB specification
   976	and the supplemental processor-specific specification for a particular
   977	processor architecture. These two documents constitute a specification that
   978	should be used in conjunction with the publicly-available standards documents
   979	it references. The LSB enumerates the system components it includes, but
   980	descriptions of those components may be included entirely in the LSB, partly in
   981	the LSB and partly in other documents, or entirely in other reference
   982	documents.
   983	
   984	II. Low Level System Information
   985	
   986	Table of Contents
   987	2. Machine Interface
   988	3. Function Calling Sequence
   989	4. Operating System Interface
   990	5. Process Initialization

   993	8. Debug Information
   994	
   995	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   996	
   997	Chapter 2. Machine Interface
   998	
   999	Data Representation
  1000	
  1001	LSB-conforming applications shall use the data representation as defined in
  1002	Chapter 3 of the System V Application Binary Interface - Intel386 Architecture
  1003	Processor Supplement.
  1004	
  1005	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1006	
  1007	Fundamental Types
  1008	
  1009	In addition to the fundamental types specified in Chapter 3 of the System V
  1010	Application Binary Interface - Intel386 Architecture, these additional data
  1011	types are defined here.
  1012	
  1013	Table 2-1. Scalar Types
  1014	
  1015	+---------------------------------------------------------------------------+
  1016	|Type    |C                 |sizeof|Alignment (bytes)|IntelI386 Architecture|
  1017	|--------+------------------+------+-----------------+----------------------|
  1018	|Boolean |bool              |1     |1                |signed byte           |
  1019	|--------+------------------+------+-----------------+----------------------|
  1020	|        |long long         |      |                 |                      |
  1021	|        |------------------|8     |4                |signed double word    |
  1022	|Integral|signed long long  |      |                 |                      |
  1023	|        |------------------+------+-----------------+----------------------|
  1024	|        |unsigned long long|8     |4                |unsigned double word  |
  1025	+---------------------------------------------------------------------------+
  1026	
  1027	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1028	
  1029	Aggregates and Unions
  1030	
  1031	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1032	
  1033	Bit Fields
  1034	
  1035	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1036	
  1037	Member Pointers
  1038	
  1039	A pointer to data member is an offset from the base address of the class object
  1040	containing it, represented as a ptrdiff_t. It has the size and alignment
  1041	attributes of a ptrdiff_t. A NULL pointer is represented as -1.
  1042	
  1043	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1044	
  1045	Class Representation
  1046	
  1047	A C++ Class is represented by several closely related data objects.
  1048	
  1049	Table 2-2. Class Components
  1050	
  1051	+--------------------------------+
  1052	|Type|C                    | | | |
  1053	|----+---------------------+-+-+-|
  1054	|4   |unsigned double word | | | |
  1055	+--------------------------------+
  1056	
  1057	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  1062	in Chapter 3 of the System V Application Binary Interface - Intel386
  1063	Architecture Processor Supplement.

  1273	III. Base Libraries
  1274	
  1275	Table of Contents
  1276	9. Libraries
  1277	
  1278	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1279	
  1280	Chapter 9. Libraries
  1281	
  1282	An LSB-conforming implementation shall support some base libraries which
  1283	provide interfaces for accessing the operating system, processor and other
  1284	hardware in the system.
  1285	
  1286	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1287	
  1288	Interfaces for libstdcxx
  1289	
  1290	Table 9-1. libstdcxx Definition
  1291	
  1292	+------------------------+
  1293	|Library:|libstdcxx      |
  1294	|--------+---------------|
  1295	|SONAME: |libstdc++.so.5 |
  1296	+------------------------+
  1297	
  1298	All symbols are in the std:: namespace.
  1299	
  1300	The behavior of the interfaces in this library is specified by the following
  1301	standards.
  1302	
  1303	ISO/IEC 14882: 1998(E) Programming languages --C++[1]
  1304	Linux Standard Base[2]

 14001	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14002	
 14003	Data Definitions for libstdcxx
 14004	
 14005	This section contains standard data definitions that describe system data.
 14006	These definitions are organized into groups that correspond to system headers.
 14007	This convention is used as a convenience for the reader, and does not imply the
 14008	existence of these headers, or their content.
 14009	
 14010	ISO C serves as the LSB reference programming language, and data definitions
 14011	are specified in ISO C format. The C language is used here as a convenient
 14012	notation. Using a C language description of these data objects does not
 14013	preclude their use by other programming languages.
 14014	
 14015	IV. System Initialization
 14016	
 14017	Table of Contents
 14018	10. System Initialization
 14019	
 14020	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14021	
 14022	Chapter 10. System Initialization
 14023	
 14024	Cron Jobs
 14025	
 14026	Packages may not touch the configuration file /etc/crontab, nor may they modify
 14027	the files in /var/spool/cron/crontabs.
 14028	
 14029	If a package wants to install a job that has to be executed via cron, it shall
 14030	place a file in one of the following directories:
 14031	
 14032	/etc/cron.daily
 14033	/etc/cron.weekly
 14034	/etc/cron.monthly
 14035	
 14036	As these directory names say, the files within them are executed on a daily,
 14037	weekly, or monthly basis, respectively. See below for the rules concerning the
 14038	names of these files.
 14039	
 14040	 If a certain job has to be executed more frequently than daily, the package
 14041	shall install a file /etc/cron.d/cron-name tagged as configuration file. This
 14042	file uses the same syntax as /etc/crontab and is processed by cron
 14043	automatically.
 14044	
 14045	It is recommended that files installed in any of these directories be scripts
 14046	(shell scripts, Perl scripts, etc.) so that they may be modified by the local
 14047	system administrator. In addition, they must be registered as configuration
 14048	file.
 14049	
 14050	The scripts in these directories have to check, if all necessary programs are
 14051	installed before they try to execute them. Otherwise, problems will arise when
 14052	a package was removed (but not purged), since the configuration files are kept
 14053	on the system in this situation.
 14054	
 14055	To avoid namespace conflicts in the /etc/cron.* directories, the filenames used
 14056	by LSB-compliant packages in /etc/cron.daily, /etc/cron.weekly, /etc/
 14057	cron.monthly, or /etc/cron.d must come from a managed namespace. These
 14058	filenames may be assigned using one of the following methods:
 14059	
 14060	  * Assigned namespace. This namespace consists of names which only use the
 14061	    character set [a-z0-9]. In order to avoid conflicts these cron script names
 14062	    must be reserved through the Linux Assigned Names and Numbers Authority
 14063	    (LANANA). Information about the LANANA may be found at www.lanana.org.
 14064	   
 14065	    Commonly used names shall be reserved in advance; developers for projects
 14066	    should be encouraged reserve names from LANA, so that each distribution can
 14067	    use the same name, and to avoid conflicts with other projects.
 14068	   
 14069	  * Hierarchical namespace. This namespace consists of scripts names which look
 14070	    like this: [hier1]-[hier2]-...-[name], where name is again taken the
 14071	    character set [a-z0-9], and where there may be one or more [hier-n]
 14072	    components. [hier1] may either be an LSB provider name assigned by the
 14073	    LANANA, or it may be owners' DNS name in lower case, with at least one '.'.
 14074	    I.e., "debian.org", "staroffice.sun.com", etc. The LSB provider name
 14075	    assigned by LANANA must only consist of the ASCII characters [a-z0-9].
 14076	   
 14077	  * Reserved namespace. This namespace consists of script names which begin
 14078	    with the character '_', and is reserved for distribution use only. This
 14079	    namespace should be used for core packages only, and in general use of this
 14080	    namespace is highly discouraged.
 14081	   
 14082	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14083	
 14084	Init Script Actions
 14085	
 14086	Init files provided by LSB applications shall accept one argument, saying what
 14087	to do:
 14088	
 14089	start        start the service                                                 
 14090	stop         stop the service                                                  
 14091	restart      stop and restart the service if the service is already running,   
 14092	             otherwise start the service                                       
 14093	try-restart  restart the service if the service is already running             
 14094	reload       cause the configuration of the service to be reloaded without     
 14095	             actually stopping and restarting the service                      
 14096	force-reload cause the configuration to be reloaded if the service supports    
 14097	             this, otherwise restart the service                               
 14098	status       print the current status of the service                           
 14099	
 14100	The start, stop, restart, force-reload, and status commands must be supported
 14101	by all init files; the reload and the try-restart options are optional. Other
 14102	init script actions may be defined by the init script. If the service is not
 14103	running the reload and the force-reload commands should not start the service.
 14104	
 14105	Init files must ensure that they will behave sensibly if invoked with start
 14106	when the service is already running, or with stop when it isn't, and that they
 14107	don't kill unfortunately-named user processes. The best way to achieve this is
 14108	to use the init-script functions provided by /lib/lsb/init-functions.
 14109	
 14110	If a service reloads its configuration automatically (as in the case of cron,
 14111	for example), the reload option of the init file must behave as if the
 14112	configuration has been reloaded successfully.
 14113	
 14114	These executable files must not fail obscurely when the configuration files
 14115	remain but the package has been removed, as the default in [the packaging
 14116	system] is to leave configuration files on the system after the package has
 14117	been removed. Only when it is executed with the [purge] option will [the
 14118	packaging system] remove configuration files. Therefore, you should include a
 14119	test statement at the top of the file, like this:
 14120	test -f program-executed-later-in-file || exit 5
 14121	or take the equivalent action if the init file is not a shell script.
 14122	
 14123	If the status command is given, the init script will return the following exit
 14124	status codes.
 14125	
 14126	0       program is running or service is OK           
 14127	1       program is dead and /var/run pid file exists  
 14128	2       program is dead and /var/lock lock file exists
 14129	3       program is not running                        
 14130	4       program or service status is unknown          
 14131	5-99    reserved for future LSB use                   
 14132	100-149 reserved for distribution use                 
 14133	150-199 reserved for application use                  
 14134	200-254 reserved                                      
 14135	
 14136	In the case of init script commands other than "status" (i.e., "start", "stop",
 14137	"restart", "reload", and "force-reload"), the init script must return an exit
 14138	status of zero if the action described by the argument has been successful.
 14139	Otherwise, the exit status shall be non-zero, as defined below. In addition to
 14140	straightforward success, the following situations are also to be considered
 14141	successful:
 14142	
 14143	  * restarting a service (instead of reloading it) with the "force-reload"
 14144	    argument
 14145	   
 14146	  * running "start" on a service already running
 14147	   
 14148	  * running "stop" on a service already stopped or not running
 14149	   
 14150	  * running "restart" on a service already stopped or not running
 14151	   
 14152	 
 14153	
 14154	In case of an error, while processing any init script action except for
 14155	"status", the init script must print an error message and return one of the
 14156	following non-zero exit status codes.
 14157	
 14158	1       generic or unspecified error (current practice)
 14159	2       invalid or excess argument(s)                  
 14160	3       unimplemented feature (for example, "reload")  
 14161	4       user had insufficient privilege                
 14162	5       program is not installed                       
 14163	6       program is not configured                      
 14164	7       program is not running                         
 14165	8-99    reserved for future LSB use                    
 14166	100-149 reserved for distribution use                  
 14167	150-199 reserved for application use                   
 14168	200-254 reserved                                       
 14169	
 14170	Error and status messages should be printed with the logging functions such as
 14171	log_failure_msg and so on. Scripts may write to standard error or standard
 14172	output, but implementations need not present text written to standard error/
 14173	output to the user or do anything else with it.
 14174	
 14175	Since init files may be run manually by a system administrator with
 14176	non-standard environment variable values for PATH, USER, LOGNAME, etc. init
 14177	files must not depend on the values of these environment variables. They should
 14178	set them to some known/default values if they are needed. 
 14179	
 14180	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14181	
 14182	Comment conventions for init scripts
 14183	
 14184	LSB applications which need to execute script(s) at bootup and/or shutdown may
 14185	provide one or more init.d files. These files are installed by the
 14186	install_initd program described below, which copies it into a standard
 14187	directory and makes whatever other adjustments (creation of symlinks, creation
 14188	of entries in a database, etc.) are necessary so that the script can be run at
 14189	boot-time. [3]
 14190	
 14191	In the init.d file, information about the shell script shall be delimited by
 14192	the lines "### BEGIN INIT INFO" and "### END INIT INFO". These delimiter lines
 14193	may containg trailing whitespace, which shall be ignored. Inside this block
 14194	there shall be lines of the form "# {keyword}: [arg1] [arg2] ...". (All lines
 14195	inside this block start with a hash ('#') character in the first column, so
 14196	that shell treats them as comments.) There must be exactly one space character
 14197	between "#" and the keyword.[4] The following keywords, with their arguments
 14198	are defined in this specification:
 14199	
 14200	        # Provides: boot_facility_1 [ boot_facility_2 ...]
 14201	        # Required-Start: boot_facility_1 [ boot_facility_2 ...]
 14202	        # Required-Stop: boot_facility_1 [ boot_facility_2 ...]
 14203	        # Should-Start: boot_facility_1 [ boot_facility_2 ...]
 14204	        # Should-Stop: boot_facility_1 [ boot_facility_2 ...]
 14205	        # Default-Start: run_level_1 [ run_level_2 ...]
 14206	        # Default-Stop: run_level_1 [ run_level_2 ...]
 14207	        # Short-Description: short_description
 14208	        # Description: multiline_description
 14209	
 14210	Additional keywords may be defined in future LSB specifications. Distributions
 14211	may define local extensions by using the prefix "X-[distribution name]" --- for
 14212	example, "X-RedHat-foobardecl", or "X-Debian-xyzzydecl".
 14213	
 14214	An init.d shell script may declare using the "Required-Start: " header that it
 14215	must not be run until certain boot facilities are provided. This information is
 14216	used by the installation tool or the boot-time boot-script execution facility
 14217	to assure that init scripts are run in the correct order. When an init script
 14218	is run with a "start" argument, the boot facility or facilities specified in
 14219	the "Provides" header shall be considered present, and hence init scripts which
 14220	require those boot facilities would then be eligble to be run. When an init
 14221	script is run with a "stop" argument, the boot facilities specified in the
 14222	"Provides" header are considered no longer present. There are naming
 14223	conventions for boot facilities and system facilities, as described in a
 14224	following section.
 14225	
 14226	Similarly, the "Required-Stop:" header defines which facilities must still be
 14227	available during the shutdown of that service. Hence, the init script system
 14228	should avoid stopping shell scripts which provide those facilities until this
 14229	shell script is stopped.
 14230	
 14231	The "Should-Start:" header defines which facilities if present should be
 14232	started before this service. This allows for weak dependencies which do not
 14233	cause the service to fail if a facility is not available. But may cause reduced
 14234	functionality of the service. Compliant applications should not rely on the
 14235	existence of this feature.
 14236	
 14237	The "Should-Stop:" header defines which facilities should be still available
 14238	during the shutdown of that service.
 14239	
 14240	The "Default-Start" and "Default-Stop" headers define which run levels should
 14241	by default run the script with a start or stop argument, respectively, to start
 14242	or stop the services controlled by the init script.
 14243	
 14244	The "Short-Description" and "Description" header fields are used to provide
 14245	text which describes the actions of the init script. The "short_description"
 14246	shall be a relatively short, pithy description of the init script, where as the
 14247	"multiline_description" can be a much longer piece of text that may span
 14248	mulitple lines. In a multiline description, each continuation line must begin
 14249	with a '#' followed by tab character or a '#' followed by at least two space
 14250	characters. The multiline description is terminated by the first line that does
 14251	not match this criteria.
 14252	
 14253	The comment conventions described in this session are only required for use by
 14254	LSB-compliant applications; system init scripts as provided by LSB-compliant
 14255	run-time environments are not required to use the scheme outlined here.
 14256	
 14257	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14258	
 14259	Installation and removal of init.d files
 14260	
 14261	An init.d file is installed by copying it into /etc/init.d (which may be a
 14262	symlink to another location). This can be done by the package installer. During
 14263	the package's postinstall script, the program "/usr/lib/lsb/install_initd"
 14264	configures the distribution's boot script system to call the package's init.d
 14265	file at the appropriate time.
 14266	
 14267	The install_initd program takes a single argument, the pathanme to the /etc/
 14268	init.d file. For example:
 14269	
 14270	        /usr/lib/lsb/install_initd /etc/init.d/example.com-coffeed
 14271	
 14272	The install_initd program shall return an exit status of zero if the init.d
 14273	file has been successfully installed or if the the init.d file was already
 14274	installed. If the required boot facilities cannot be fulfilled an exit status
 14275	of one shall be returned and the init.d file shall not be installed.
 14276	
 14277	When a software package is removed, the package's preuninstall script shall
 14278	call /usr/lib/lsb/remove_initd and pass the pathname to the /etc/init.d file.
 14279	The package manager is still responsible for removing the /etc/init.d file; the
 14280	remove_initd program is provided in case the distribution needs to clean up any
 14281	other modifications in the distribution's boot script system that might have
 14282	been made by the install_initd program. For example:
 14283	
 14284	        /usr/lib/lsb/remove_initd /etc/init.d/example.com-coffeed
 14285	
 14286	The remove_initd program shall return an exit status of zero if the init.d file
 14287	has been successfully removed or if the the init.d file is not installed. If
 14288	another init.d file which depends on a boot facility provided by this init.d
 14289	file is installed, an exit status of one shall be returned and the init.d file
 14290	shall remained installed.
 14291	
 14292	There should be a tool available to the user (e.g., RedHat's chkconfig) which
 14293	can be used by the system administrator to easily manipulate at which init
 14294	levels a particular init.d script is started or stopped. This specification
 14295	currently does not specify such an interface, however.
 14296	
 14297	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14298	
 14299	Run Levels
 14300	
 14301	 The following run levels are specified for use by the "Default-Start:" and
 14302	"Default-Stop:" specifiers as defined by the section Comment conventions for
 14303	init scripts>. Many LSB run-time environments commonly use these run level
 14304	definitions, and in the absence of other considerations, providers of run-time
 14305	environments are strongly encouraged to follow this convention to provide
 14306	consistency for system administrators who need to work with multiple
 14307	distributions. However, it is not required that LSB-compliant run-time
 14308	environments use these run levels; the distribution-provided install_initd
 14309	script may map the run levels specified below to whatever
 14310	distribution-specified run levels are most appropriate. 
 14311	
 14312	0 halt                                                    
 14313	1 single user mode                                        
 14314	2 multiuser with no network services exported             
 14315	3 normal/full multiuser                                   
 14316	4 reserved for local use, default is normal/full multiuser
 14317	5 multiuser with xdm or equivalent                        
 14318	6 reboot                                                  
 14319	
 14320	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14321	
 14322	Facility names
 14323	
 14324	Boot facilities are used to indicate dependencies in init scripts, as defined
 14325	in a previous section. Facility names that begin with a dollar sign ('$') are
 14326	system facility names, defined by the LSB, and MUST be provided by
 14327	distributions. [5] LSB applications must not provide facilities that begin with
 14328	a dollar sign. This document defines the following facility names:
 14329	
 14330	$local_fs  all local filesystems are mounted                                   
 14331	$network   low level networking (ethernet card; may imply PCMCIA running)      
 14332	$named     daemons which may provide hostname resolution (if present) are      
 14333	           running                                                             
 14334	$portmap   daemons providing SunRPC/ONCRPC portmapping service[6] (if present) 
 14335	           are running                                                         
 14336	$remote_fs all remote filesystems are mounted[7].                              
 14337	$syslog    system logger is operational                                        
 14338	$time      the system time has been set [8]                                    
 14339	
 14340	Other (non-system) facilities may be defined by other LSB applications. These
 14341	facilities shall be named using the same conventions defined for naming init.d
 14342	script names. Commonly, the facility provided by an LSB application init.d
 14343	script will have the same name as the name assigned to the init.d script.
 14344	
 14345	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14346	
 14347	Script names
 14348	
 14349	Since the init.d scripts must live in a single directory, they must come from a
 14350	single namespace. Three means of assigning names from this namespace are
 14351	available:
 14352	
 14353	  * Assigned namespace. This namespace consists of names which only use the
 14354	    character set [a-z0-9]. This space is desirable for scripts which system
 14355	    administrators may often wish to run manually: e.g., "/etc/init.d/named
 14356	    restart" In order to avoid conflicts these init.d names must be reserved
 14357	    through the Linux Assigned Names and Numbers Authority (LANANA).
 14358	    Information about the LANANA may be found at www.lanana.org.
 14359	   
 14360	    Commonly used names shall be reserved in advance; developers for projects
 14361	    should be encouraged to reserve names from LANANA, so that each
 14362	    distribution can use the same name, and to avoid conflicts with other
 14363	    projects.
 14364	   
 14365	  * Hierarchical namespace. This namespace consists of scripts names which look
 14366	    like this: [hier1]-[hier2]-...-[name], where name is again taken the
 14367	    character set [a-z0-9], and where there may be one or more [hier-n]
 14368	    components. [hier1] may either be an LSB provider name assigned by the
 14369	    LANANA, or it may be owners' DNS name in lower case, with at least one '.'
 14370	    (e.g., "debian.org", "staroffice.sun.com"). The LSB provider name assigned
 14371	    by LANANA must only consist of the ASCII characters [a-z0-9].
 14372	   
 14373	  * Reserved namespace. This namespace consists of script names which begin
 14374	    with the character '_', and is reserved for distribution use only. This
 14375	    namespace should be used for core packages only, and in general use of this
 14376	    namespace is highly discouraged.  
 14377	   
 14378	In general, if a package or some system function is likely to be used on
 14379	multiple systems, the package developers or the distribution SHOULD get a
 14380	registered name through LANANA, and distributions should strive to use the same
 14381	name whenever possible. For applications which may not be "core" or may not be
 14382	commonly installed, the hierarchical namespace may be more appropriate. An
 14383	advantage to the hierarchical namespace is that there is no need to consult
 14384	with the LANANA before obtaining an assigned name.
 14385	
 14386	Short names are highly desirable, since many system administrators like to use
 14387	them to manually start and stop services. Given this, they should be
 14388	standardized on a per-package basis. This is the rationale behind having a
 14389	LANANA organization to assign these names. The LANANA may be called upon to
 14390	handle other namespace issues, such as package/prerequisites naming (which is
 14391	essential to making prerequisites to work correctly).
 14392	
 14393	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 14394	
 14395	Init script Functions
 14396	
 14397	Each LSB-compliant init.d script must source the file /lib/lsb/init-functions.
 14398	This file must cause the following shell script commands to be defined. This
 14399	can be done either by adding a directory to the PATH variable which defines
 14400	these commands, or by defining sh aliases. While the distribution-provided
 14401	aliases may choose to use bash extensions (at the distribution's option), the
 14402	LSB init.d files themselves should only depend in /bin/sh features as defined
 14403	by POSIX.2.
 14404	
 14405	                This runs the specified program as a daemon. start_daemon will 
 14406	start_daemon    check to see if the program is already running using the       
 14407	[-f] [-n        algorithm given by pidofproc. If so, it will not start another 
 14408	nicelevel] [-p  copy of the daemon unless the -f option is given. The -n option
 14409	pidfile]        specifies a nice level. See nice(1). start_daemon should return
 14410	pathname [args] the LSB defined exit status codes. It shall return 0 if the    
 14411	                program has been successfully started or is running and not 0  
 14412	                otherwise.                                                     
 14413	                This stops the specified program. The program is found using   
 14414	                the algorithm given by pidofproc. If a signal is specified,    
 14415	                using the -signal_name or -signal_number syntaxes specified by 
 14416	killproc [-p    the kill command, the program is sent that signal. Otherwise, a
 14417	pidfile]        SIGTERM followed by a SIGKILL after some number of seconds is  
 14418	pathname        sent. Compliant applications may use the basename instead of   
 14419	[signal]        the pathname. killproc should return the LSB defined exit      
 14420	                status codes. If called without a signal, it shall return 0 if 
 14421	                the program has been stopped or is not running and not 0       
 14422	                otherwise. If a signal is given, it shall return 0 only if the 
 14423	                program is running.                                            
 14424	                This function returns one or more pid(s) for a particular      
 14425	                daemon. If an entry is found in /var/run/basename.pid, then    
 14426	                that value is returned. If the -p option is used, the given    
 14427	                pidfile is used instead. Compliant applications may use the    
 14428	                basename instead of the pathname. Compliant implementations of 
 14429	                the LSB may attempt other mechanisms for determining the pid   
 14430	pidofproc [-p   (s), although this is not required (and not recommended, since 
 14431	pidfile]        a user can trick startup scripts by creating processes that    
 14432	pathname        appear to be system programs in the process list thus creating 
 14433	                a potential security exposure). Hence, LSB-complaint           
 14434	                applications who wish to use the pidofproc function in their   
 14435	                init scripts must store the pid in /var/run/basename.pid.      
 14436	                multiple pids should be separated by a single space. pidofproc 
 14437	                should return the LSB defined exist status codes for "status". 
 14438	                It shall return 0 if the program is running and not 0          
 14439	                otherwise.                                                     
 14440	log_success_msg This requests the distribution to print a success message. The 
 14441	"message"       message should be relatively short; no more than 60 characters 
 14442	                is highly desirable.                                           
 14443	log_failure_msg This requests the distribution to print a failure message. The 
 14444	"message"       message should be relatively short; no more than 60 characters 
 14445	                is highly desirable.                                           
 14446	log_warning_msg This requests the distribution to print a warning message. The 
 14447	"message"       message should be relatively short; no more than 60 characters 
 14448	                is highly desirable.                                           
 14449	
 14450	Notes
 14451	
 14452	[1]  ISO/IEC 14882: 1998(E) Programming languages --C++                        
 14453	                                                                               
 14454	[2]  Linux Standard Base                                                       
 14455	                                                                               
 14456	[3]  This specification does not require, but is designed to allow, the        
 14457	     development of a system which runs boot scripts in parallel. Hence,       
 14458	     enforced-serialization of scripts is avoided unless it is explicitly      
 14459	     necessary.                                                                
 14460	                                                                               
 14461	[4]  More than one space, or a tab character, indicates the continuation line. 
 14462	                                                                               
 14463	[5]  The dollar sign does not indicate variable expansion as in many Linux     
 14464	     utilities. Starting a facility name with a dollar sign is merely a way of 
 14465	     dividing the namespace between the system and applications.               
 14466	                                                                               
 14467	[6]  as defined in RFC 1833                                                    
 14468	                                                                               
 14469	[7]  In some LSB run-time environments, filesystems such as /usr may be remote.
 14470	     Many applications that require $local_fs will probably require also       
 14471	     require $remote_fs                                                        
 14472	                                                                               
 14473	[8]  i.e., using a network-based time program such as ntp or rdate, or via the 
 14474	     hardware Real Time Clock                                                  
 14475
